,Recommended,441870,22070722,"Posted: 26 March, 2016",all,34 y/o Military Cyborg Ninja,"There's a strong battle between pros and cons with this game. I'm recommending it simply because the developer did put  time in creating this game. He used his skills to get the word out about some new song artists that are trying to make it in this world. However, there's a lot of room for improvement.This game seems to be more about the music rather than the actual controls or gameplay.The pros:-Colorful, and alive background-Good music-Good concept/story-Cool, easy to use UI-Easy to pick up/redirect yourself if you get stuck (usually)-I do like the concept of when your car stops or crashes, the screen dims (her life is ending if you don't get yer sh#t together man!) and the music slows down. The music will also speed up when your car is overheating.-The ""life"" meter is simple to follow, but has room for improvement.The cons:-The car (controls) does not handle so well at times. (Sometimes if you hit the wall, your car will spin all the way around, but a pro is that you can easily redirect it) It feels like you're skating on ice.-Hard to see road blocks (You may not have enough time to react to it)-Having to redo your settings each time you start up the game (gamers usually like their setup to be remembered)The developer himself mentions above that this isn't technically a game, but more so a music/aesthetic experiement. I do believe that this ""game"" has a potential to actually be a game though. If the developer focuses on fixing it or tuning it, I will definitely play more of it in the future. As I said, the concept is very cool. I also believe the game would be better if we didn't have to worry so much about hitting the walls. You run into them quite frequently. (Or maybe I'm just that clumsy?) But I suppose it's better than falling off the track every 30 seconds.Now if you're looking for an inexpensive way to listen to music and enjoy some neon scenery, here you go.Note: You DO see the helicopter in the game (I found it about 7-8 minutes into my ride, but it isn't too threatening)."
,Not Recommended,441870,28681748,"Posted: 26 December, 2016",all,Giggles,"Here is my review of OutDrive: (Do note, that if you are somewhat offended or think my review is wrong in any way, try not to get triggered by it, and tell me why in the comment area)Good ConceptThe game has a good concept, being set in an ""Aesthetic"" synthwave 80's era, I do genuinely think that the concept of this game is great! Although that being said, it should be noted that everything inside it can become repetitive. As a quote-on-quote fan of the synthwave style of music, I do like the setting of the game as a wholeSoundtrackAs I mentioned earlier, I do like the synthwave genre of music with songs such as ""Decay"" by HOME and their other song ""Resonance"" I do find however, that the soundtrack is a bit repetitive and sounds god awful when it slows down (More on that later) I also find that (In my opinion) that the music is to fast to be classed as synthwave, but I suppose that it's due to the fact that it's a driving game. I do wish they had implemented music from HOME and others into the game, but again, that's my opinionGame MechanicsEh... They are not the best in the world, I don't know if it's because its coded in Unity (A personal displeasure to me and doesn't say as far as I know on the store page), if it's because it's a driving game, or if I am terrible at driving games. The idea of this game is to keep your girlfriend(I assume?) alive by driving your car, you also have to keep the icon in the blue area (Or the safe zone or whatever) or it can go into the red zones by either; over heating, or going to slow, to stop this, you have to either slow down, or speed up. That is essentially what you have to do, also, did I mention that you can also make the icon go into the low red by hitting something, no? Me neither! as far as I know, it doesn't mention that anywhere at all and I didn't know that, until I lost the game because of that, bare in mind, that the physics of the game itself and the driving mechanics are VERY wonky, and don't really work with a keyboard and would be best played with something like an Xbox controller or a Steam Machine or Steam Link, then again it might just be me. To me also, it's counter intuative to have it so that the icon goes into the low red when you hit a wall when the mechanics are god awful, well that's in my opinion.Conclusion/OverallOverall, I don't personally recommend this game, it's not suited for PC, but would be better as some sort of indie game on console's, but overall, I like the style, not so much the game its self. But don't let my opinon deter you from this game. Oh and also, while you're reading this review, you might want to get this game on sale, for it's low price at the start, I wouldn't say it's worth it (I got it for 49 pence, bet you can tell where I come from now ( ͡° ͜ʖ ͡°))If I had to give it a score out of 10, maybe something along the lines of a 4-5/10"
